Brand spankin new.  Staff flits about like hummingbirds, primping, tidying, friendlying up patronage with check-ins and cookie samples.     There's a real executive chef supervising the highly visible goings on behind the glass partition between the dining and food prep areas.  There is real pro-culinary experience back there.  The breads are baked fresh on premises daily.       A surprising amount of variety can be found in the menu, with all the usuals, plus a few nifties like the Meaty Spud, a crispy-shell bbq-taco-salad thing, or a 10 oz burger.       The breads are baked fresh on premises daily.        Lunch prices were very reasonable for a sandwhich+side+drink combo.  Take home prices for meat were a little less thrifty. They make batches for each day and don't keep food for the next day, though, so if you come in 3-4pm you get a discount on the selection that does remain.     There will be tweaking with a place this new, such as a conversation Daren and I had with Chef J about kicking up his special sauce a notch or two on the heat, which he happily heard us say, since he'd originally had it much hotter, and told us to plan for it to be next time.       We've got our eye on the burger, which Chef J and the owner both talked up as a custom crafted 80/20 chuck recipe that will endure minimal processing or handling, never frozen, cooked over a charcoal grill.  Guess where and when the buns are freshly baked?

